title: Production of 111In and 114mIn by proton induced reactions: an update on excitation functions, chemical separation - purification and recovery of target material

x4freetext: Production of 111In and 114mIn by proton induced
reactions: an update on excitation functions, chemical
separation - purification and recovery of target
material

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary
Catholic Univ. of Louvain, Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium

x4freetext: Enriched 112Cd elecroplated onto Cu backing with
the following isotopic composition:
-48-CD-116, enrichment not given
-48-CD-114, enrichment <0.008
-48-CD-113, enrichment <0.008
-48-CD-112, enrichment >0.976
-48-CD-111, enrichment <0.006
-48-CD-110, enrichment <0.002
-48-CD-108, enrichment not given
-48-CD-106, enrichment not given
Enriched 114Cd elecroplated onto Cu backing.
Two stacks
consisting of 112Cd on Cu-backing targets interleaved
with Al degraders, were irradiated with a 36.7 MeV and
25 MeV protons. The second stack contained also 114Cd
targets. Irradiation was done in a Faraday-cup type
target holder with proton beams of 100nA for 40 and 60
minutes. Beam intensity was monitored by using Cu
monitor reactions. Activity was measured with no
chemical separation. Several series of spectra were
recorded to be able to follow the decay. Decay data
were taken from NUDAT online data library.

x4codes.shortRef: Rept: Nuclear Data Services (Doc. series of NDS), No.1211 (2001)

x4freetext: Uncertainty on the energy scale includes
cumulative effects of initial beam energy, stopping
estimation influenced by target thickness and beam
straggling. Throughout the stack it increases from
0.2MeV for the first foil to 1.4MeV at the last foil
for the 36.7MeV irradiation and to 1.1MeV for the
25.0MeV experiment.
The uncertainty on the cross section values
are estimated in the standard way as the square root
of the quadratic summation of the independently
contributing parameters. Uncertainty of time
parameters is not included. Overall uncertainty were
surface density of target nuclei(5%),
incident charged particle flux (7%),
nuclear decay and branching data(3%)
detector efficiency (5%)
statistical and peak fitting (2-8%)
The experimental data were compared to the
results of the theoretical model codes TENDL-2012.
The measured experimental data were compared to
those found in the literature.
